Down a short alley.  With a large pink cotton candy machine. Sits a small restaurant.  The one waitress is surly.  We tried desperately for a smile, and felt vidicated at the end when we finally won one.  But the chef, a tiny lady with a huge smile makes the best of food.  The sake is great and served in large portions.  The grapefruit chu-hi is with fresh juice.  Do not leave without trying the pork belly, the tofu ground pork stir-fry, and saba (whole fish).  The gyoza were perfectly fried on one side and soft on the other two.  The portions are all perfect.  The prices are more than reasonable.  And when you leave you get to make your own cotton candy (put the sugar in the middle black cup and turn it on).  A win for sure.

Awesome hole in the wall restaurant. It's kind of hidden but I remember from my last visit in Waikiki seeing it and telling myself I had to come back and try it. And I'm so glad I did, because it was amazing. Food and service was great. Felt like I was back in Japan again. I'll definitely have to go back and try out more of their menu items. And I for sure recommend everyone who enjoys Japanese food and drinks to go here. And if the experience wasn't great already, when they dropped the check off, they gave us flavored sugar to make our own cotton candy! It was just a fun experience, great food and service, and the environment was cute and clean.

Very nice little Izakaya with a cute interior and nice seating. Great happy hour from 5p-7p daily with korean and Japanese eats.  Takoyaki is wonderful, service is great. Much better experience than any of the highly rated boring Waikiki beach bars. My one complaint, garlic shrimp was overdone. But all other dishes were grand: kimchi, takoyaki, Chan chan yaki, and shrimp shumi.  Update: making your own cotton candy at the end, super fun!

Honolulu often falls victim to its popularity in that average and overpriced food receives high ratings from unsophisticated palates. This is not to say mine is a precision taste weapon or anything, but I've been around the block a time or two and bristle when I see lousy chains like Tommy Bahama pull down nearly five stars. Let this serve as the context to what I'm about to say.  Pau Hana Base is an oasis in the mediocrity. It is a neighborhood izakaya just like the ones I've been to in Tokyo. It is quiet, charming, friendly, affordable, and the food is both delicious and diverse. Do yourself a favor: skip the glitz and glamor of Waikiki's main drag to come here instead. You won't be disappointed.
